ğŸ§  What is State in React?

**State** is a built-in React object that is used to **store dynamic data** in a component.

ğŸ“Œ State can change over time
ğŸ“Œ When state changes â†’ Component re-renders

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ†š State vs Props

| State                    | Props                   |
| ------------------------ | ----------------------- |
| Managed inside component | Passed from parent      |
| Can change               | Read-only               |
| Local                    | External                |
| Triggers re-render       | Also triggers re-render |

ğŸ“Œ Props = Data from outside
ğŸ“Œ State = Data inside component

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”· State in Functional Components (Modern Way â­)

React uses **Hooks** to manage state.

---

ğŸ§¾ useState Syntax

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";

const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue);
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§ª Simple Counter Example

```jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{count}</h2>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increment
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

ğŸ“Œ `count` â†’ current state
ğŸ“Œ `setCount` â†’ function to update state

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” How State Works Internally

1. Initial render
2. User clicks button
3. `setCount()` updates state
4. React creates new Virtual DOM
5. UI updates automatically

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  Multiple State Variables

```jsx
const [name, setName] = useState("");
const [age, setAge] = useState(0);
```

ğŸ“Œ Each state is independent

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ“¦ State with Objects

```jsx
const [user, setUser] = useState({
  name: "",
  age: 0
});
```

Updating Object State

```jsx
setUser({
  ...user,
  name: "Saakshi"
});
```

ğŸ“Œ Always use **spread operator**
âŒ Donâ€™t overwrite entire object unintentionally

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ“š State with Arrays

```jsx
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
```

Add Item

```jsx
setItems([...items, "New Item"]);
```

ğŸ“Œ Never mutate array directly
âŒ `items.push()`

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” Updating State Based on Previous State

```jsx
setCount(prevCount => prevCount + 1);
```

ğŸ“Œ Recommended when:

* Updating based on previous value
* Multiple updates

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  State in Class Components (Recap)

```jsx
class Counter extends React.Component {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.state = { count: 0 };
  }

  render() {
    return (
      <button onClick={() =>
        this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 })
      }>
        {this.state.count}
      </button>
    );
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âš ï¸ Important Rules About State

âœ” Never modify state directly
âœ” Always use `setState` or setter function
âœ” State updates are asynchronous
âœ” State change causes re-render

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ Re-rendering in React

Component re-renders when:

* State changes
* Props change
* Parent re-renders

ğŸ“Œ React updates only changed parts (Virtual DOM)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Common Beginner Mistakes

âŒ Modifying state directly
âŒ Forgetting spread operator
âŒ Overusing state
âŒ Storing derived data in state
âŒ Infinite re-renders

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

âœ” Keep state minimal
âœ” Use one responsibility per state
âœ” Use functional updates
âœ” Keep state close to where itâ€™s used
âœ” Avoid unnecessary re-renders

